WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:23.200
The Mutiny on the Bounty Copyright Black Cat Publishing

00:23.200 --> 00:45.040
Chapter 1

00:45.040 --> 00:47.760
The Ship

00:47.760 --> 00:54.000
It was a cold morning in the winter of 1787.

00:54.000 --> 01:00.160
Tom Barnes was very excited when he arrived at Spithead.

01:00.160 --> 01:04.640
Tom wanted to find his ship, the Bounty.

01:04.640 --> 01:08.680
He stopped an old sailor with a friendly face.

01:08.680 --> 01:12.400
Excuse me, where's the Bounty?

01:12.400 --> 01:14.240
Tom asked.

01:14.240 --> 01:18.160
The sailor looked at Tom's new uniform and he smiled.

01:18.160 --> 01:20.360
How old are you?

01:20.360 --> 01:21.600
He asked him.

01:21.600 --> 01:23.440
I'm fourteen.

01:23.440 --> 01:25.600
Replied Tom.

01:25.600 --> 01:26.960
Come with me.

01:26.960 --> 01:28.800
The sailor said.

01:28.800 --> 01:32.160
The Bounty is over there, I think.

01:32.160 --> 01:36.200
Tom and the sailor walked together towards a large ship.

01:36.200 --> 01:38.120
Ah, yes.

01:38.120 --> 01:40.640
The sailor said after a while.

01:40.640 --> 01:42.960
There she is.

01:42.960 --> 01:45.320
Who is she?

01:45.320 --> 01:47.240
Tom asked him.

01:47.240 --> 01:50.640
We call all the ships she.

01:50.640 --> 01:52.480
The sailor explained.

01:52.480 --> 01:55.120
And you must do the same.

01:55.120 --> 01:58.320
That's how real sailors talk.

01:58.320 --> 02:01.240
Soon they arrived at the Bounty.

02:01.240 --> 02:05.320
A sailor saw Tom and saluted politely.

02:05.320 --> 02:10.800
Tom saluted the sailor back and turned to the old sailor.

02:10.880 --> 02:12.400
Thank you for your help.

02:12.400 --> 02:14.160
He said to him.

02:14.160 --> 02:19.920
He looked up at the Bounty for a moment and then turned back to the old sailor.

02:19.920 --> 02:22.760
She's so big.

02:22.760 --> 02:25.560
The old sailor smiled at him.

02:25.560 --> 02:27.520
You learn quickly.

02:27.520 --> 02:29.000
He told him.

02:29.000 --> 02:32.160
That's one of the two things you must do.

02:32.160 --> 02:35.880
Learn everything you can.

02:35.880 --> 02:39.320
And what's the second thing I must do?

02:39.320 --> 02:41.040
Tom asked him.

02:41.040 --> 02:42.520
That's easy.

02:42.520 --> 02:44.400
The old sailor replied.

02:44.400 --> 02:48.200
Oh, bay, your captain.

02:48.200 --> 02:52.600
The old sailor walked away from Tom.

02:52.600 --> 02:55.440
Learn and obey.

02:55.440 --> 02:57.200
Tom thought.

02:57.200 --> 02:59.760
It's good advice.

02:59.760 --> 03:03.120
Now Tom went inside the Bounty.

03:03.120 --> 03:07.040
He walked on the deck and looked up at the masts.

03:07.040 --> 03:09.280
They were very tall.

03:09.280 --> 03:13.040
He knew that all the sailors had to climb them.

03:13.040 --> 03:16.400
For a moment he was afraid.

03:16.400 --> 03:17.960
But I can learn.

03:17.960 --> 03:20.640
He decided.

03:20.640 --> 03:23.840
Then he went down below the deck.

03:23.840 --> 03:26.720
He wanted to find his cabin.

03:26.720 --> 03:30.440
It was dark and there were a lot of sailors there.

03:30.440 --> 03:34.440
The sailors were noisy and Tom was frightened of them.

03:34.440 --> 03:38.600
They were men and he was only a boy.

03:38.600 --> 03:41.640
Suddenly the sailors were silent.

03:41.640 --> 03:44.800
They looked at someone behind Tom.

03:44.800 --> 03:48.760
Tom turned round and saw an officer.

03:48.760 --> 03:51.760
The officer was a young man.

03:51.760 --> 03:56.720
He smiled at the men and then he looked kindly at Tom.

03:56.720 --> 03:58.680
You must be Tom Barnes.

03:58.680 --> 03:59.800
He said.

03:59.800 --> 04:02.080
I'm Fletcher Christian.

04:02.080 --> 04:05.480
I can show you the ship if you want.

04:05.520 --> 04:09.720
I've got time before the captain comes aboard.

04:09.720 --> 04:10.720
Yes please.

04:10.720 --> 04:12.040
Tom agreed.

04:12.040 --> 04:15.080
I want to know everything about her.

04:15.080 --> 04:18.800
Mr. Christian laughed.

04:18.800 --> 04:19.800
That's good.

04:19.800 --> 04:20.800
He said.

04:20.800 --> 04:24.680
A young man needs to know his ship well.

04:24.680 --> 04:28.080
His ship and the men in her.

04:28.080 --> 04:32.640
Mr. Christian and Tom walked around the ship together.

04:32.640 --> 04:36.360
Mr. Christian showed Tom the ship's cannons.

04:36.360 --> 04:39.200
They stood next to one of the cannons.

04:39.200 --> 04:42.720
There were two sailors on the other side of the deck.

04:42.720 --> 04:46.120
But they did not see the officer and Tom.

04:46.120 --> 04:48.760
My brother knows Blighy.

04:48.760 --> 04:50.840
One of the sailors said.

04:50.840 --> 04:53.840
But you don't know him George.

04:53.840 --> 04:55.480
The other sailor said.

04:55.480 --> 04:58.880
You don't know the captain.

04:58.880 --> 05:01.760
He's the worst captain in the Navy.

05:01.760 --> 05:03.720
The first sailor continued.

05:03.720 --> 05:08.680
My brother told me Blighy is cruel.

05:08.680 --> 05:09.880
Andy uses the winner a lot.

05:09.880 --> 05:11.440
That's enough talk.

05:11.440 --> 05:14.520
Mr. Christian said loudly to the two sailors.

05:14.520 --> 05:17.880
Go up on deck and help the other men.

05:17.880 --> 05:19.400
Yes sir.

05:19.400 --> 05:22.160
The sailors replied quickly.

05:22.160 --> 05:23.560
Brave men Tom.

05:23.560 --> 05:25.680
Mr. Christian repeated.

05:25.680 --> 05:27.000
Brave men.

05:27.000 --> 05:30.000
And it's our responsibility to keep them happy.

05:32.760 --> 05:35.760
Chapter Two.

05:35.760 --> 05:39.760
Captain Bligh.

05:39.760 --> 05:43.760
Tom was very busy in the next few days.

05:43.760 --> 05:48.760
The sailors worked hard to prepare the ship for the long voyage.

05:48.760 --> 05:51.760
And Tom worked hard too.

05:51.760 --> 05:56.760
His friend Mr. Christian taught him many things.

05:56.760 --> 06:00.760
One day he showed Tom how to climb the masts.

06:00.760 --> 06:03.760
Tom was afraid at first.

06:03.760 --> 06:06.760
Then he climbed up to the top of the mast.

06:06.760 --> 06:10.760
The port looked very small from up there.

06:10.760 --> 06:16.760
The young officer also taught Tom about navigation.

06:16.760 --> 06:19.760
They spent a lot of time together.

06:19.760 --> 06:24.760
Mr. Christian was kind and Tom liked him.

06:24.760 --> 06:28.760
Tom watched his friend with the sailors.

06:28.760 --> 06:33.760
Fletcher Christian told them what to do because that was his job.

06:33.760 --> 06:38.760
But he was always polite and the sailors liked him.

06:38.760 --> 06:41.760
Be good to the men Tom.

06:41.760 --> 06:43.760
His friend advised him.

06:43.760 --> 06:45.760
Sailors are brave men.

06:45.760 --> 06:48.760
We must treat them well.

06:48.760 --> 06:52.760
Captain Bligh came aboard on the third day.

06:52.760 --> 06:55.760
He did not smile when he met the officers.

06:55.760 --> 07:01.760
He went immediately to his cabin and he stayed there the whole day.

07:01.760 --> 07:08.760
Later Tom heard a conversation between the sailor called George and some other sailors.

07:08.760 --> 07:10.760
Bligh is back.

07:10.760 --> 07:12.760
George said.

07:12.760 --> 07:16.760
He does not look very happy to see us.

07:16.760 --> 07:18.760
I know him.

07:18.760 --> 07:20.760
Be careful of him.

07:20.760 --> 07:23.760
He is a terror.

07:23.760 --> 07:25.760
What's the captain like?

07:25.760 --> 07:27.760
Tom asked Fletcher Christian.

07:27.760 --> 07:33.760
One of the sailors said that Captain Bligh is one of the best officers in the Navy.

07:33.760 --> 07:34.760
Fletcher told him.

07:34.760 --> 07:36.760
I know him well.

07:36.760 --> 07:38.760
He looked at Tom.

07:38.760 --> 07:43.760
Sometimes the sailors don't understand their officers Tom.

07:43.760 --> 07:47.760
A captain's job is a difficult one you know.

07:47.760 --> 07:52.760
That evening Tom ate with all the officers in the captain's cabin.

07:53.760 --> 07:58.760
There was a long table and Captain Bligh sat at one end.

07:58.760 --> 08:01.760
Come and sit with me Mr. Barnes.

08:01.760 --> 08:03.760
Captain Bligh said.

08:03.760 --> 08:07.760
The youngest officer always sits with the captain.

08:07.760 --> 08:09.760
He explained.

08:09.760 --> 08:11.760
Tom sat down.

08:11.760 --> 08:14.760
He did not know what to say to the captain.

08:14.760 --> 08:17.760
Is this your first voyage?

08:17.760 --> 08:19.760
Captain Bligh asked him.

08:19.760 --> 08:21.760
Yes sir.

08:21.760 --> 08:23.760
Tom replied nervously.

08:23.760 --> 08:26.760
Captain Bligh smiled at him.

08:26.760 --> 08:29.760
You have a lot to learn my boy.

08:29.760 --> 08:31.760
The captain told him.

08:31.760 --> 08:34.760
You must ask me lots of questions.

08:34.760 --> 08:35.760
Thank you sir.

08:35.760 --> 08:37.760
Tom said.

08:37.760 --> 08:41.760
Now Captain Bligh turned to the other officers.

08:41.760 --> 08:44.760
He asked them about the ship and the sailors.

08:44.760 --> 08:47.760
Is everything ready for tomorrow?

08:47.760 --> 08:48.760
He asked.

08:48.760 --> 08:49.760
Yes sir.

08:49.760 --> 08:51.760
The officers told him.

08:51.760 --> 08:52.760
Very good.

08:52.760 --> 08:53.760
He said.

08:53.760 --> 08:55.760
He stood up.

08:55.760 --> 08:57.760
Sleep well gentlemen.

08:57.760 --> 09:00.760
We leave early in the morning.

09:00.760 --> 09:03.760
The officers left the captain's cabin.

09:03.760 --> 09:06.760
What do you think of Captain Bligh now?

09:06.760 --> 09:09.760
Fletcher Christian asked Tom.

09:09.760 --> 09:11.760
I think he's a good captain.

09:11.760 --> 09:12.760
Tom answered.

09:12.760 --> 09:15.760
He's not a terror at all.

09:19.760 --> 09:23.760
Listening activity.

09:23.760 --> 09:30.760
Dear Mum, I hope you're all well and not missing me too much.

09:30.760 --> 09:36.760
The ship is very big, but I can find my way around now.

09:36.760 --> 09:43.760
I'm learning a lot, but I have to get up very early.

09:43.760 --> 09:48.760
I met some sailors on the first day I arrived,

09:48.760 --> 09:54.760
and the officer I work with is very friendly.

09:54.760 --> 10:00.760
Today I learned how to calculate the position of the ship.

10:00.760 --> 10:06.760
It's difficult, but I think I understand it now.

10:06.760 --> 10:12.760
The officer I work with is called Fletcher Christian.

10:12.760 --> 10:20.760
He also showed me how to climb masts, and today I climbed right to the top.

10:20.760 --> 10:23.760
It was amazing.

10:23.760 --> 10:28.760
Yesterday I sat next to Captain Bligh.

10:28.760 --> 10:31.760
He's a good captain.

10:31.760 --> 10:34.760
He's very famous in the Navy.

10:34.760 --> 10:39.760
The other sailors say, he's a terror,

10:39.760 --> 10:43.760
but I'm sure he's not that bad.

10:43.760 --> 10:48.760
He's kind to me, so don't worry.

10:48.760 --> 10:52.760
I think I'm going to enjoy my voyage.

10:52.760 --> 10:58.760
I'll be able to send this letter at the next port.

10:58.760 --> 11:02.760
Give my love to Charlotte and Jane.

11:02.760 --> 11:04.760
Don't worry about me.

11:04.760 --> 11:09.760
I'm happy with my new life on board the ship,

11:09.760 --> 11:13.760
and I'm sure everything will be fine.

11:13.760 --> 11:18.760
I'll bring you all some presents when I return.

11:18.760 --> 11:24.760
Love, Tom.

11:24.760 --> 11:29.760
Chapter 3, the voyage begins.

11:29.760 --> 11:36.760
It was the 23rd of December 1787 when the bounty left Britain,

11:36.760 --> 11:40.760
and the ship quickly left land far behind.

11:40.760 --> 11:43.760
The days passed quickly for Tom.

11:43.760 --> 11:46.760
He climbed the masts easily now.

11:46.760 --> 11:49.760
He was not afraid of Captain Bligh anymore,

11:49.760 --> 11:54.760
and he sat next to the captain every evening at dinner.

11:54.760 --> 11:57.760
Learn your navigation, Mr. Barnes.

11:57.760 --> 11:59.760
The captain told him one evening.

11:59.760 --> 12:03.760
It's the most important thing for an officer.

12:03.760 --> 12:07.760
You must always know the position of the ship.

12:07.760 --> 12:13.760
One day, Tom and Fletcher Christian were next to Captain Bligh on the deck.

12:13.760 --> 12:16.760
The captain had his sextant in his hand.

12:16.760 --> 12:19.760
He explained to Tom how to use it.

12:19.760 --> 12:22.760
We want to know our position.

12:22.760 --> 12:27.760
He said, I can find out with this sextant.

12:27.760 --> 12:30.760
First, I must find the sun.

12:30.760 --> 12:33.760
He pointed the instrument at the sun.

12:33.760 --> 12:37.760
Then he wrote some numbers on a piece of paper.

12:37.760 --> 12:39.760
Now it's your turn.

12:39.760 --> 12:41.760
He said to Tom.

12:41.760 --> 12:44.760
Tom took the sextant and pointed it at the sun.

12:44.760 --> 12:49.760
Then he too wrote some numbers on a piece of paper.

12:49.760 --> 12:51.760
Where are we, Mr. Barnes?

12:51.760 --> 12:54.760
Captain Bligh asked him.

12:54.760 --> 12:57.760
Tom showed the captain his piece of paper.

12:57.760 --> 13:00.760
The captain studied it for a moment.

13:00.760 --> 13:02.760
His face was serious.

13:02.760 --> 13:04.760
This is no good?

13:04.760 --> 13:06.760
He shouted angrily.

13:06.760 --> 13:09.760
You must do better than this.

13:09.760 --> 13:11.760
Then he turned to Fletcher Christian.

13:11.760 --> 13:15.760
His boy can't use the sextant properly.

13:15.760 --> 13:18.760
He said, teach him, Mr. Christian.

13:18.760 --> 13:21.760
Is your responsibility?

13:21.760 --> 13:25.760
Captain Bligh moved away from Tom and Fletcher.

13:25.760 --> 13:27.760
Tom was very unhappy.

13:27.760 --> 13:29.760
Don't worry.

13:29.760 --> 13:33.760
Fletcher told him, we can practice later today.

13:33.760 --> 13:38.760
Captain Bligh did not talk to Tom for the rest of the day.

13:38.760 --> 13:42.760
He still looked angry when they met at dinner.

13:42.760 --> 13:44.760
He is a terror.

13:44.760 --> 13:46.760
Tom thought.

13:46.760 --> 13:50.760
A few days later, Tom was on deck with the captain again.

13:50.760 --> 13:52.760
Well, Mr. Barnes.

13:52.760 --> 13:56.760
Captain Bligh said, are you ready for some navigation?

13:56.760 --> 13:58.760
Yes, sir.

13:58.760 --> 14:00.760
Tom answered.

14:00.760 --> 14:02.760
This time Tom was lucky.

14:02.760 --> 14:07.760
He wrote the numbers down and gave the piece of paper to the captain.

14:07.760 --> 14:11.760
Captain Bligh studied the numbers silently.

14:11.760 --> 14:13.760
Then he smiled at Tom.

14:13.760 --> 14:15.760
Well done, my boy.

14:15.760 --> 14:19.760
He said, your calculation is correct.

14:19.760 --> 14:21.760
It's a good piece of work.

14:21.760 --> 14:27.760
Tom was very pleased and his friend Fletcher was happy for him as well.

14:27.760 --> 14:31.760
That evening Captain Bligh was very cheerful.

14:31.760 --> 14:37.760
He told Tom stories about fights between enemy ships and adventures.

14:37.760 --> 14:41.760
He talked about beautiful islands in the Pacific Ocean.

14:41.760 --> 14:44.760
They are wonderful places, my boy.

14:44.760 --> 14:50.760
He said, the people are friendly, the sun shines all day,

14:50.760 --> 14:54.760
and there is always fruit on the trees.

14:54.760 --> 14:58.760
That night Captain Bligh asked Tom to wait in the cabin.

14:58.760 --> 15:02.760
I want to show you my collection, Mr. Barnes.

15:02.760 --> 15:04.760
The captain told him.

15:04.760 --> 15:07.760
He took Tom to the back of the cabin.

15:07.760 --> 15:10.760
There were hundreds of plants there.

15:10.760 --> 15:13.760
They come from all over the world.

15:13.760 --> 15:15.760
Captain Bligh told him proudly.

15:15.760 --> 15:17.760
They're my hobby.

15:17.760 --> 15:21.760
He pointed to a large plant with blue flowers.

15:21.760 --> 15:23.760
This is my favorite.

15:23.760 --> 15:24.760
He said.

15:24.760 --> 15:27.760
It comes from a little island in the Pacific.

15:27.760 --> 15:31.760
It's more than ten years old.

15:31.760 --> 15:34.760
The captain's not so bad, really.

15:34.760 --> 15:37.760
Tom thought he gets angry sometimes.

15:37.760 --> 15:39.760
That's all.

15:43.760 --> 15:46.760
Listening activity.

15:46.760 --> 15:53.760
Go two squares south west.

15:53.760 --> 16:01.760
Now follow on two squares to the west.

16:01.760 --> 16:08.760
Turn south east for four squares.

16:08.760 --> 16:14.760
Go north again for one square.

16:14.760 --> 16:21.760
Now turn north east for two squares.

16:21.760 --> 16:26.760
And north for one square.

16:26.760 --> 16:33.760
This is the position of the ship.

16:33.760 --> 16:35.760
Chapter four.

16:35.760 --> 16:39.760
Punishment at sea.

16:39.760 --> 16:44.760
One day Fletcher and Tom were in Fletcher's cabin together.

16:44.760 --> 16:48.760
Fletcher took a map out of the desk.

16:48.760 --> 16:50.760
Come and look at this, Tom.

16:50.760 --> 16:51.760
He said.

16:51.760 --> 16:54.760
Tom sat next to his friend.

16:54.760 --> 16:56.760
We're going here.

16:56.760 --> 16:58.760
Fletcher explained.

16:58.760 --> 17:02.760
He pointed to a little island in the sea.

17:02.760 --> 17:04.760
This is Tahiti.

17:04.760 --> 17:09.760
It's one of the most beautiful islands in the world.

17:09.760 --> 17:13.760
We're going there to collect breadfruit plants.

17:13.760 --> 17:18.760
Then we're going to take them all the way to the west Indies.

17:18.760 --> 17:21.760
That's our mission.

17:21.760 --> 17:23.760
What's Tahiti like?

17:23.760 --> 17:25.760
Tom wanted to know.

17:25.760 --> 17:28.760
It's a beautiful island.

17:28.760 --> 17:32.760
Sailors are always happy to stop there.

17:32.760 --> 17:36.760
And the people of Tahiti are very friendly.

17:36.760 --> 17:40.760
Just then they heard Captain Bligh's voice.

17:40.760 --> 17:42.760
He was on the deck above them.

17:42.760 --> 17:45.760
He was angry with one of the sailors.

17:45.760 --> 17:48.760
That water is for the plants.

17:48.760 --> 17:49.760
He shouted.

17:49.760 --> 17:53.760
It isn't for you to drink.

17:53.760 --> 17:55.760
I'm sorry, sir.

17:55.760 --> 17:57.760
The sailor said nervously.

17:57.760 --> 18:00.760
Tom recognized the sailor's voice.

18:00.760 --> 18:02.760
It was George.

18:02.760 --> 18:04.760
Mr. Christian.

18:04.760 --> 18:06.760
Captain Bligh shouted.

18:06.760 --> 18:08.760
Come onto the deck, please.

18:08.760 --> 18:10.760
Fletcher ran out of the cabin.

18:10.760 --> 18:13.760
He went on deck and Tom followed him.

18:13.760 --> 18:15.760
Arrest that man.

18:15.760 --> 18:17.760
Captain Bligh ordered.

18:17.760 --> 18:20.760
Fletcher called two of the sailors.

18:20.760 --> 18:23.760
Take this man to the captain's cabin.

18:23.760 --> 18:25.760
He told them.

18:25.760 --> 18:28.760
The sailors tied George's hands together.

18:28.760 --> 18:31.760
Then they took him down to the captain's cabin.

18:31.760 --> 18:34.760
Captain Bligh was still angry.

18:34.760 --> 18:37.760
He turned to speak to Fletcher Christian.

18:37.760 --> 18:40.760
I want discipline on this ship.

18:40.760 --> 18:41.760
He told him.

18:41.760 --> 18:45.760
And it's your job to control the sailors.

18:45.760 --> 18:49.760
Fletcher did not reply to the angry words.

18:49.760 --> 18:52.760
We must punish that sailor.

18:52.760 --> 18:54.760
The captain said.

18:54.760 --> 18:58.760
You know what to do, Mr. Christian.

18:58.760 --> 19:02.760
Fletcher Christian did not want to punish the sailor.

19:02.760 --> 19:04.760
He tried to argue with the captain.

19:04.760 --> 19:07.760
There's a lot of water on the ship, sir.

19:07.760 --> 19:08.760
He said.

19:08.760 --> 19:11.760
The sailor doesn't deserve punishment.

19:11.760 --> 19:14.760
Punish him, Mr. Christian.

19:14.760 --> 19:16.760
The captain said.

19:16.760 --> 19:17.760
Yes, sir.

19:17.760 --> 19:20.760
Fletcher said unhappily.

19:20.760 --> 19:26.760
That afternoon all the officers stood on the deck around Captain Bligh.

19:26.760 --> 19:29.760
Two sailors brought George onto the deck.

19:29.760 --> 19:32.760
They tied him to one of the masts.

19:32.760 --> 19:35.760
Then another sailor stepped forward.

19:35.760 --> 19:42.760
He had a cruel whip, a catter nine tails, in his hand.

19:42.760 --> 19:47.760
You must whip him twenty times as his punishment.

19:47.760 --> 19:50.760
Captain Bligh told the sailor.

19:50.760 --> 19:52.760
Very good, sir.

19:52.760 --> 19:54.760
The sailor replied.

19:54.760 --> 19:59.760
He raised the catter nine tails, then he hit George on the back.

19:59.760 --> 20:02.760
George cried out.

20:02.760 --> 20:05.760
But he continued to hit him.

20:05.760 --> 20:08.760
Tom watched the punishment.

20:08.760 --> 20:11.760
He was frightened when he saw blood on the deck.

20:11.760 --> 20:13.760
He closed his eyes.

20:13.760 --> 20:16.760
He did not want to look anymore.

20:16.760 --> 20:18.760
It's all right, Tom.

20:18.760 --> 20:19.760
Fletcher told him.

20:19.760 --> 20:22.760
The punishment is nearly finished.

20:22.760 --> 20:26.760
Captain Bligh counted as the sailor hit George.

20:26.760 --> 20:28.760
Nineteen.

20:28.760 --> 20:30.760
Twenty.

20:30.760 --> 20:32.760
He called out.

20:32.760 --> 20:35.760
Now take him away.

20:35.760 --> 20:38.760
Some sailors ran forward.

20:38.760 --> 20:41.760
They untied George from the mast.

20:41.760 --> 20:45.760
He could not walk, so the sailors carried him away.

20:45.760 --> 20:50.760
Chapter five.

20:50.760 --> 20:54.760
An unhappy ship.

20:54.760 --> 20:58.760
The sailors were not happy after George's punishment.

20:58.760 --> 21:03.760
They still did their work, but they looked angrily at the captain.

21:03.760 --> 21:06.760
Tom was not happy either.

21:06.760 --> 21:09.760
He talked to Fletcher Christian.

21:09.760 --> 21:12.760
Captain Bligh's a cruel man.

21:12.760 --> 21:14.760
He told his friend.

21:14.760 --> 21:16.760
Don't talk like that.

21:16.760 --> 21:17.760
Fletcher told him.

21:17.760 --> 21:20.760
He's our captain, and we must obey him.

21:20.760 --> 21:24.760
Tom remembered the advice of the old sailor.

21:24.760 --> 21:29.760
Obey your captain.

21:29.760 --> 21:33.760
Soon after, there was a terrible storm at sea.

21:33.760 --> 21:38.760
The wind was very strong, and the waves came onto the ship.

21:38.760 --> 21:40.760
It was cold and wet.

21:40.760 --> 21:45.760
The crew of the bounty fought the storm for thirty days and nights.

21:45.760 --> 21:49.760
Nobody could sleep, and there was no hot food.

21:49.760 --> 21:55.760
The sailors worked hard to save the ship, and everyone was exhausted.

21:55.760 --> 21:58.760
We're all going to die.

21:58.760 --> 22:01.760
Thought Tom.

22:01.760 --> 22:05.760
One day there was a terrible accident.

22:05.760 --> 22:09.760
Captain Bligh ordered some sailors to climb the masts.

22:09.760 --> 22:14.760
It was difficult and dangerous, and they climbed slowly in the wind.

22:14.760 --> 22:19.760
Suddenly, one of the sailors fell from the mast.

22:19.760 --> 22:21.760
He was very badly hurt.

22:21.760 --> 22:26.760
The doctor tried to help him, but he died.

22:26.760 --> 22:30.760
Tom saw George and his friend together.

22:30.760 --> 22:32.760
Bligh's a bad captain.

22:32.760 --> 22:34.760
George said angrily.

22:34.760 --> 22:37.760
He doesn't care about the men.

22:37.760 --> 22:40.760
He's a hard man, George.

22:40.760 --> 22:41.760
His friend replied.

22:41.760 --> 22:43.760
We all know that.

22:43.760 --> 22:45.760
But what can we do?

22:45.760 --> 22:47.760
He's the captain.

22:47.760 --> 22:49.760
I know what we can do.

22:49.760 --> 22:55.760
George said he took out his knife and showed it to his friend.

22:55.760 --> 22:56.760
Put that away.

22:56.760 --> 22:58.760
His friend said quickly.

22:58.760 --> 23:01.760
You mustn't talk like that.

23:01.760 --> 23:06.760
At last, the storm passed, and the weather was calm again.

23:06.760 --> 23:10.760
The bounty sailed towards Tahiti.

23:10.760 --> 23:17.760
Tom thought the ship's problems were over, but the good weather brought new difficulties.

23:17.760 --> 23:24.760
One evening at dinner, Fletcher Christian talked seriously to the captain.

23:24.760 --> 23:27.760
There's a problem with the water, sir.

23:27.760 --> 23:28.760
He said.

23:28.760 --> 23:33.760
Some of the barrels are broken because of the storm.

23:33.760 --> 23:36.760
Do we have enough water to reach Tahiti?

23:36.760 --> 23:38.760
The captain asked.

23:38.760 --> 23:40.760
We can reach Tahiti.

23:40.760 --> 23:42.760
Fletcher told him.

23:42.760 --> 23:45.760
But we must give the sailors all the water.

23:45.760 --> 23:49.760
We can't give water to the plants, sir.

23:49.760 --> 23:50.760
No.

23:50.760 --> 23:52.760
Shouted Captain Bligh angrily.

23:52.760 --> 23:54.760
The plants are important.

23:54.760 --> 23:57.760
The crew must drink less water.

23:57.760 --> 24:01.760
Two cups a day for each sailor, Mr. Christian.

24:01.760 --> 24:03.760
Two cups a day?

24:03.760 --> 24:05.760
It's not enough, sir.

24:05.760 --> 24:06.760
Fletcher said.

24:06.760 --> 24:10.760
The men need more than two cups a day to survive.

24:10.760 --> 24:12.760
Give the order, Mr. Christian.

24:12.760 --> 24:14.760
Captain Bligh replied.

24:14.760 --> 24:17.760
Two cups a day.

24:17.760 --> 24:22.760
The next day, Fletcher Christian explained the order to the sailors.

24:22.760 --> 24:24.760
They were not happy.

24:24.760 --> 24:27.760
Two cups a day, sir.

24:27.760 --> 24:29.760
One of them asked.

24:29.760 --> 24:32.760
We can't work without water.

24:32.760 --> 24:34.760
It's not right.

24:34.760 --> 24:37.760
What about the captain's plants, sir?

24:37.760 --> 24:40.760
Another sailor wanted to know.

24:40.760 --> 24:42.760
Do we still give them water?

24:42.760 --> 24:45.760
The plants get their water.

24:45.760 --> 24:47.760
Fletcher told them.

24:47.760 --> 24:49.760
We're more important than plants.

24:49.760 --> 24:52.760
A sailor said angrily.

24:52.760 --> 24:55.760
Fletcher looked sadly at the men.

24:55.760 --> 24:58.760
He agreed with them.

24:58.760 --> 25:00.760
Captain's orders, men.

25:00.760 --> 25:02.760
He said.

25:05.760 --> 25:08.760
Listening activity.

25:09.760 --> 25:11.760
This is Island Radio.

25:11.760 --> 25:15.760
Well, we've got plenty of music for you today on Island Radio,

25:15.760 --> 25:18.760
but first, Jane Venders with the weather.

25:18.760 --> 25:20.760
Good morning.

25:20.760 --> 25:24.760
Now, the weather isn't looking too bad for the next 24 hours,

25:24.760 --> 25:27.760
and the temperatures are high for this time of year.

25:27.760 --> 25:31.760
But it will depend on where you are on the island today.

25:31.760 --> 25:35.760
The north of the island will be mostly clear and sunny all day,

25:35.760 --> 25:38.760
with clear skies until midnight.

25:38.760 --> 25:44.760
In the east, there will be a mixture of sunshine and outbreaks of rain in the morning,

25:44.760 --> 25:47.760
but becoming sunnier in the afternoon.

25:47.760 --> 25:53.760
The west of the island will have the worst of the rain with heavy rain until midday.

25:53.760 --> 25:56.760
There will be some sun in the afternoon and late evening,

25:56.760 --> 25:59.760
but it will continue to be cloudy.

25:59.760 --> 26:03.760
In the south, the weather will be cloudy in the morning,

26:03.760 --> 26:08.760
but sunnier later in the afternoon, with strong winds near the coast.

26:08.760 --> 26:13.760
That's all from me until tomorrow and now back to Mike.

26:17.760 --> 26:19.760
Chapter 6.

26:19.760 --> 26:21.760
Tahiti.

26:23.760 --> 26:25.760
It was very hot on the ship.

26:25.760 --> 26:31.760
There were no clouds in the sky and the sun shone all day.

26:31.760 --> 26:36.760
The sailors worked hard, and they were always thirsty.

26:36.760 --> 26:39.760
They wanted more water.

26:40.760 --> 26:44.760
Captain Bligh was always angry now.

26:44.760 --> 26:51.760
He did not talk to Tom in his cabin, and very often he shouted at Fletcher Christian.

26:51.760 --> 26:56.760
The officers were extremely unhappy.

26:56.760 --> 27:07.760
At last, on the 26th of October, 1788, the bounty reached the island of Tahiti.

27:07.760 --> 27:09.760
Tom was excited.

27:09.760 --> 27:12.760
He saw trees on the island.

27:12.760 --> 27:16.760
Soon there were a lot of canoes in the sea.

27:16.760 --> 27:21.760
The people of Tahiti came across the sea to welcome the sailors.

27:21.760 --> 27:26.760
They brought fruit and flowers with them and gave them to the sailors.

27:26.760 --> 27:29.760
The ship anchored near the island.

27:29.760 --> 27:32.760
Everything will be all right now.

27:32.760 --> 27:34.760
George said to his friend,

27:34.760 --> 27:38.760
Tahiti is the best place in the world.

27:38.760 --> 27:42.760
The sailors looked at the island and smiled happily.

27:42.760 --> 27:47.760
Some of them knew the island well, and they told their friends about it.

27:47.760 --> 27:49.760
It's wonderful.

27:49.760 --> 27:51.760
One of them explained.

27:51.760 --> 27:53.760
The people like sailors.

27:53.760 --> 27:59.760
We can eat and drink good things here, and the people are friendly.

27:59.760 --> 28:03.760
Fletcher Christian went to talk to the captain.

28:03.760 --> 28:06.760
The men like Tahiti.

28:06.760 --> 28:08.760
He said to Captain Bligh.

28:08.760 --> 28:11.760
They want to go on to the island.

28:11.760 --> 28:14.760
Can I give permission, sir?

28:14.760 --> 28:17.760
No one can go on to the island yet.

28:17.760 --> 28:19.760
Captain Bligh replied.

28:19.760 --> 28:23.760
We have work to do, Mr. Christian.

28:23.760 --> 28:25.760
The sailors are tired, sir.

28:25.760 --> 28:27.760
Fletcher said.

28:27.760 --> 28:30.760
They need rest and good food.

28:30.760 --> 28:33.760
Can't they go there for a few days?

28:33.760 --> 28:36.760
Didn't you hear me, Mr. Christian?

28:36.760 --> 28:38.760
Captain Bligh asked angrily.

28:38.760 --> 28:43.760
No one will go to the island without my permission.

28:43.760 --> 28:47.760
Tom heard Captain Bligh's angry words to his friend.

28:47.760 --> 28:50.760
He was sorry for Fletcher.

28:50.760 --> 28:54.760
Just then, some sailors came to Tom and Fletcher.

28:54.760 --> 28:57.760
When can we go to the island, sir?

28:57.760 --> 29:00.760
One of the sailors asked Fletcher.

29:00.760 --> 29:02.760
I know the island well.

29:02.760 --> 29:04.760
I've got friends here.

29:04.760 --> 29:06.760
I'm sorry, men.

29:06.760 --> 29:07.760
Fletcher replied.

29:07.760 --> 29:10.760
No one can go yet.

29:10.760 --> 29:12.760
Captain's orders.

29:12.760 --> 29:14.760
The men were angry.

29:14.760 --> 29:17.760
But we always visit the island.

29:17.760 --> 29:19.760
One of them argued?

29:19.760 --> 29:21.760
It's not right.

29:21.760 --> 29:25.760
Captain Bligh was soon busy with the islanders.

29:25.760 --> 29:28.760
He wanted to buy lots of breadfruit plants.

29:28.760 --> 29:31.760
The islanders brought lots of the plants,

29:31.760 --> 29:34.760
and the sailors carried them on to the ship.

29:34.760 --> 29:36.760
More plants.

29:36.760 --> 29:39.760
George said to his friend.

29:39.760 --> 29:43.760
One day, Captain Bligh decided to go ashore.

29:43.760 --> 29:46.760
He wanted Tom to go with him.

29:46.760 --> 29:50.760
They took one of the bounties' little boats.

29:50.760 --> 29:54.760
A group of islanders met them when they came ashore.

29:54.760 --> 29:57.760
The islanders gave them presents.

29:57.760 --> 30:02.760
Then they showed the captain and Tom around the island.

30:02.760 --> 30:06.760
Tom thought that Tahiti was very beautiful.

30:06.760 --> 30:10.760
Even Captain Bligh seemed happy.

30:10.760 --> 30:13.760
This is my favorite place.

30:13.760 --> 30:15.760
He told Tom.

30:15.760 --> 30:19.760
Tom thought about the sailors on the ship.

30:19.760 --> 30:22.760
They wanted to come to the island, too.

30:22.760 --> 30:25.760
The men like the island, too.

30:25.760 --> 30:28.760
He said, they want to come here, sir.

30:28.760 --> 30:30.760
Captain Bligh laughed.

30:30.760 --> 30:32.760
Don't worry about them.

30:32.760 --> 30:33.760
He told Tom.

30:33.760 --> 30:36.760
They can come here soon.

30:36.760 --> 30:39.760
But first, they must work.

30:39.760 --> 30:41.760
Discipline, Mr. Barnes.

30:41.760 --> 30:43.760
Discipline.

30:43.760 --> 30:45.760
The captain's all right.

30:45.760 --> 30:49.760
Tom thought he's not a terror after all.

30:52.760 --> 30:54.760
Chapter 7.

30:54.760 --> 30:57.760
Trouble in Tahiti.

30:57.760 --> 30:59.760
Weeks passed.

30:59.760 --> 31:02.760
The bounty had lots of breadfruit plants now,

31:02.760 --> 31:05.760
and Captain Bligh was happy.

31:05.760 --> 31:09.760
One day, he called Fletcher Christian.

31:09.760 --> 31:12.760
The sailors can go to the island now.

31:12.760 --> 31:14.760
He told Fletcher.

31:14.760 --> 31:15.760
Thank you, sir.

31:15.760 --> 31:17.760
Fletcher said,

31:17.760 --> 31:22.760
he went to the sailors and told them the good news.

31:22.760 --> 31:26.760
Soon Tom saw the bounties' little boats in the water.

31:26.760 --> 31:31.760
They were full of sailors carrying presents for the islanders.

31:31.760 --> 31:35.760
The sailors went to the island every day now,

31:35.760 --> 31:38.760
and they made friends with the islanders.

31:38.760 --> 31:40.760
They ate good food.

31:40.760 --> 31:43.760
The islanders liked the sailors,

31:43.760 --> 31:46.760
and they played music for them.

31:46.760 --> 31:50.760
Some of the sailors fell in love with girls on the island.

31:50.760 --> 31:52.760
The months passed,

31:52.760 --> 31:55.760
and the bounty stayed in Tahiti.

31:55.760 --> 31:57.760
We can't leave yet.

31:57.760 --> 31:59.760
Fletcher explained to Tom.

31:59.760 --> 32:02.760
We must wait for the right wind.

32:02.760 --> 32:05.760
The sailors were happy to wait.

32:05.760 --> 32:09.760
Some of them spent all their time on the island now.

32:09.760 --> 32:13.760
They did not return to the ship.

32:13.760 --> 32:17.760
One day, three sailors decided to escape.

32:17.760 --> 32:20.760
They wanted to live on the island.

32:20.760 --> 32:24.760
They took one of the ship's boats and some guns.

32:24.760 --> 32:29.760
Captain Bligh was furious and wanted to punish them.

32:29.760 --> 32:33.760
He ordered Fletcher Christian to find them.

32:33.760 --> 32:38.760
Fletcher Christian and Tom went to the island together.

32:38.760 --> 32:40.760
We must find them, Tom.

32:40.760 --> 32:43.760
Fletcher said sadly.

32:43.760 --> 32:48.760
Fletcher and Tom found the three sailors on the island

32:48.760 --> 32:51.760
and brought them back to the bounty.

32:51.760 --> 32:55.760
Once again, Captain Bligh ordered a punishment

32:55.760 --> 32:57.760
with the cationine tails.

32:57.760 --> 33:01.760
The other sailors watched the punishment.

33:01.760 --> 33:03.760
They were sorry for the three men,

33:03.760 --> 33:06.760
and they were angry with the captain.

33:06.760 --> 33:07.760
It's sad.

33:07.760 --> 33:09.760
One of the sailors said,

33:09.760 --> 33:11.760
They're not bad men.

33:11.760 --> 33:14.760
The captain's too hard.

33:14.760 --> 33:15.760
You're right.

33:15.760 --> 33:17.760
Another sailor agreed.

33:17.760 --> 33:20.760
The captain's a hard man.

33:20.760 --> 33:23.760
That night, it was very hot,

33:23.760 --> 33:25.760
and Tom could not sleep.

33:25.760 --> 33:28.760
So he walked on the deck.

33:28.760 --> 33:33.760
He heard a conversation between Fletcher Christian and George.

33:33.760 --> 33:35.760
You know I'm right.

33:35.760 --> 33:37.760
George said.

33:37.760 --> 33:40.760
It can't continually this, sir.

33:40.760 --> 33:42.760
What can we do?

33:42.760 --> 33:43.760
Fletcher asked.

33:43.760 --> 33:46.760
You know the answer to that, sir.

33:46.760 --> 33:48.760
George told him.

33:48.760 --> 33:51.760
The man are with you, Mr. Christian.

33:51.760 --> 33:53.760
How many men?

33:53.760 --> 33:55.760
Fletcher asked him.

33:55.760 --> 33:57.760
Enough, sir.

33:57.760 --> 33:59.760
George told him.

34:02.760 --> 34:04.760
Chapter eight.

34:04.760 --> 34:07.760
Tom's big decision.

34:07.760 --> 34:11.760
The bounty spent six months in Tahiti.

34:11.760 --> 34:15.760
Finally, the wind was in the right direction,

34:15.760 --> 34:19.760
and Captain Bly decided to leave the island.

34:19.760 --> 34:22.760
The sailors did not want to go back to the ship

34:22.760 --> 34:25.760
because they had friends on the island now.

34:25.760 --> 34:30.760
Some of them even wanted to marry Tahitian girls.

34:30.760 --> 34:34.760
The ship sailed away from the island.

34:34.760 --> 34:39.760
The sailors did their work, but they were silent.

34:39.760 --> 34:41.760
What's wrong with the men?

34:42.760 --> 34:45.760
Captain Bly asked Fletcher Christian one day.

34:45.760 --> 34:47.760
They're all right, sir.

34:47.760 --> 34:48.760
Fletcher told him.

34:48.760 --> 34:51.760
They just missed their friends on Tahiti.

34:51.760 --> 34:54.760
Captain Bly turned to Tom with a smile.

34:54.760 --> 34:57.760
A little navigation, Mr. Barnes.

34:57.760 --> 34:58.760
He suggested.

34:58.760 --> 35:01.760
We mustn't forget navigation.

35:01.760 --> 35:04.760
He gave Tom the sextant.

35:04.760 --> 35:06.760
Tom looked at the sun.

35:06.760 --> 35:09.760
Then he wrote some numbers on a piece of paper.

35:09.760 --> 35:11.760
He showed the paper to Bly.

35:11.760 --> 35:12.760
Well done.

35:12.760 --> 35:14.760
The captain said.

35:14.760 --> 35:17.760
You're learning, Mr. Barnes.

35:17.760 --> 35:21.760
Tom remembered the words of the old sailor at the port.

35:21.760 --> 35:24.760
Done everything you can.

35:24.760 --> 35:27.760
He was very pleased with himself.

35:27.760 --> 35:31.760
Just then, one of the sailors came onto the deck.

35:31.760 --> 35:36.760
He stopped in front of Fletcher Christian and said a few words.

35:36.760 --> 35:38.760
What is it, Mr. Christian?

35:38.760 --> 35:40.760
Captain Bly asked.

35:40.760 --> 35:42.760
What does the man want?

35:42.760 --> 35:44.760
It's the chronometer, sir.

35:44.760 --> 35:46.760
Fletcher replied.

35:46.760 --> 35:48.760
It doesn't work.

35:48.760 --> 35:50.760
Doesn't work?

35:50.760 --> 35:52.760
Shouted Bly furiously.

35:52.760 --> 35:54.760
Why doesn't it work?

35:54.760 --> 35:56.760
There's water in it.

35:56.760 --> 35:58.760
Fletcher told him.

35:58.760 --> 36:00.760
That's your responsibility.

36:00.760 --> 36:02.760
Captain Bly told him.

36:02.760 --> 36:06.760
You're the worst officer on this ship.

36:07.760 --> 36:13.760
Fletcher did not say anything, but he became red in the face.

36:13.760 --> 36:17.760
Captain Bly was angry all that day.

36:17.760 --> 36:21.760
He did not speak to Fletcher at dinner that evening.

36:21.760 --> 36:25.760
Tom was sorry for his friend.

36:25.760 --> 36:32.760
In the middle of the night, when Tom was asleep, a man came into his cabin.

36:32.760 --> 36:33.760
Wake up.

36:33.760 --> 36:35.760
The man said quietly.

36:35.760 --> 36:37.760
Wake up, Tom.

36:37.760 --> 36:39.760
Tom sat up suddenly.

36:39.760 --> 36:43.760
He looked around and saw Fletcher in the cabin.

36:43.760 --> 36:45.760
What is it?

36:45.760 --> 36:46.760
Is something wrong?

36:46.760 --> 36:47.760
He asked.

36:47.760 --> 36:49.760
Listen to me.

36:49.760 --> 36:52.760
Fletcher said very seriously.

36:52.760 --> 36:56.760
The sailors don't want to obey Captain Bly.

36:56.760 --> 37:00.760
I'm going to be Captain of the Bounty.

37:00.760 --> 37:02.760
What do you mean?

37:02.760 --> 37:05.760
Tom asked, shocked.

37:05.760 --> 37:08.760
We're going to take the ship from Captain Bly.

37:08.760 --> 37:10.760
Fletcher told him.

37:10.760 --> 37:12.760
But that's mutiny.

37:12.760 --> 37:13.760
Tom said.

37:13.760 --> 37:15.760
You can't do that, Fletcher.

37:15.760 --> 37:18.760
Don't argue with me, Tom.

37:18.760 --> 37:19.760
Fletcher said.

37:19.760 --> 37:22.760
There isn't much time.

37:22.760 --> 37:25.760
I just want to ask you one thing.

37:25.760 --> 37:29.760
Are you with me or with the captain?

37:29.760 --> 37:31.760
Tom thought hard.

37:31.760 --> 37:33.760
Fletcher was his friend.

37:33.760 --> 37:37.760
He was a good man and he was kind to the sailors.

37:37.760 --> 37:41.760
But Bly was the captain of the ship.

37:41.760 --> 37:44.760
Tom did not answer.

37:44.760 --> 37:46.760
You must tell me.

37:46.760 --> 37:48.760
Fletcher said.

37:48.760 --> 37:50.760
You must decide, Tom.

37:50.760 --> 37:54.760
It's the most important decision of your life.

37:54.760 --> 37:57.760
Tom looked at his friend.

37:57.760 --> 38:03.760
Then he remembered his conversation with the old sailor at the port.

38:03.760 --> 38:06.760
And what's the second thing I must do?

38:06.760 --> 38:08.760
Tom asked him.

38:08.760 --> 38:10.760
That's easy.

38:10.760 --> 38:12.760
The old sailor replied.

38:12.760 --> 38:15.760
Obey your captain.

38:18.760 --> 38:21.760
Listening activity.

38:21.760 --> 38:24.760
I think you're right.

38:25.760 --> 38:28.760
But it's the wrong thing to do.

38:31.760 --> 38:33.760
Yes, I understand.

38:33.760 --> 38:36.760
But I don't think that's true.

38:38.760 --> 38:42.760
Well, maybe he's not so bad.

38:42.760 --> 38:45.760
But he's not a good leader.

38:47.760 --> 38:49.760
Yes, you're right.

38:49.760 --> 38:52.760
But I don't know about that.

38:55.760 --> 38:57.760
Oh, yes.

38:57.760 --> 39:02.760
I don't think it's a good idea either.

39:05.760 --> 39:07.760
Chapter 9.

39:07.760 --> 39:10.760
The Mutiny.

39:10.760 --> 39:16.760
It was early morning on the 28th of April 1789.

39:16.760 --> 39:21.760
Captain Bly was asleep in his cabin.

39:21.760 --> 39:27.760
Suddenly Fletcher Christian and George came into the cabin.

39:27.760 --> 39:30.760
They had guns and swords with them.

39:30.760 --> 39:31.760
What is it?

39:31.760 --> 39:33.760
Shouted Captain Bly.

39:33.760 --> 39:34.760
What's wrong?

39:34.760 --> 39:36.760
This is a mutiny.

39:36.760 --> 39:38.760
Fletcher told him.

39:38.760 --> 39:40.760
I'm the captain now.

39:40.760 --> 39:43.760
How can you do this, Mr. Christian?

39:43.760 --> 39:45.760
Captain Bly asked in great surprise.

39:45.760 --> 39:48.760
We're officers in the Navy.

39:48.760 --> 39:50.760
It's too late, Captain Bly.

39:50.760 --> 39:51.760
Christian replied.

39:51.760 --> 39:54.760
I can't stand your cruelty anymore.

39:54.760 --> 39:57.760
And neither can the men.

39:57.760 --> 40:01.760
Christian and George tied the captain's hands behind his back.

40:01.760 --> 40:04.760
Then they took him onto the deck.

40:04.760 --> 40:09.760
There were other sailors there, and they had guns and swords as well.

40:09.760 --> 40:12.760
What can we do with Captain Bly?

40:12.760 --> 40:13.760
A sailor asked.

40:13.760 --> 40:15.760
We can kill him.

40:15.760 --> 40:17.760
George said.

40:18.760 --> 40:22.760
I have a wife and four children at home, Mr. Christian.

40:22.760 --> 40:25.760
Captain Bly said quietly.

40:25.760 --> 40:28.760
Are you going to kill me?

40:28.760 --> 40:29.760
No.

40:29.760 --> 40:30.760
Fletcher replied.

40:30.760 --> 40:33.760
I don't want to kill you, Captain.

40:33.760 --> 40:35.760
He thought for a moment.

40:35.760 --> 40:38.760
We can give you one of the ship's boats.

40:38.760 --> 40:40.760
He decided.

40:40.760 --> 40:42.760
George laughed.

40:42.760 --> 40:44.760
We're in the middle of the sea.

40:44.760 --> 40:45.760
He said.

40:45.760 --> 40:49.760
No one can survive in a small boat.

40:49.760 --> 40:51.760
It's too dangerous.

40:51.760 --> 40:56.760
He looked at Captain Bly and smiled cruelly.

40:56.760 --> 40:59.760
You're going to die out there, Captain.

40:59.760 --> 41:01.760
He told him.

41:01.760 --> 41:06.760
You're going to die out there, all alone.

41:06.760 --> 41:08.760
What do you want to do?

41:08.760 --> 41:11.760
Fletcher Christian asked the sailors.

41:12.760 --> 41:17.760
How many of you want to go with Captain Bly in the small boat?

41:17.760 --> 41:20.760
18 sailors came forward.

41:20.760 --> 41:22.760
We do so.

41:22.760 --> 41:24.760
They told Captain Bly.

41:24.760 --> 41:26.760
We're not mutineers.

41:26.760 --> 41:30.760
Tom looked at Fletcher Christian and the mutineers.

41:30.760 --> 41:33.760
Then he looked at Captain Bly.

41:33.760 --> 41:35.760
He thought for a moment.

41:35.760 --> 41:37.760
Then he stepped forward.

41:37.760 --> 41:40.760
I'm going with the Captain too.

41:40.760 --> 41:43.760
He told Fletcher Christian.

41:43.760 --> 41:44.760
You?

41:44.760 --> 41:45.760
Said Christian.

41:45.760 --> 41:48.760
But it's dangerous, Tom.

41:48.760 --> 41:49.760
Stay with us.

41:49.760 --> 41:51.760
You're my friend.

41:51.760 --> 41:53.760
No Fletcher.

41:53.760 --> 41:54.760
Tom replied.

41:54.760 --> 41:57.760
I must obey my captain.

41:57.760 --> 42:00.760
Soon the small boat was ready to leave.

42:00.760 --> 42:05.760
Captain Bly, Tom and the 18 sailors got into it.

42:05.760 --> 42:08.760
They had a little water and food with them

42:08.760 --> 42:12.760
and Captain Bly carried his sextant with him.

42:12.760 --> 42:16.760
Captain Bly sat at the back of the boat.

42:16.760 --> 42:18.760
He looked at Tom and the sailors.

42:18.760 --> 42:22.760
He was serious but very calm.

42:22.760 --> 42:24.760
Raised the sail?

42:24.760 --> 42:26.760
He told the sailors.

42:26.760 --> 42:30.760
The boat sailed away from the bounty.

42:30.760 --> 42:32.760
And now Mr. Barnes?

42:32.760 --> 42:35.760
Captain Bly said with a smile.

42:35.760 --> 42:37.760
Some navigation.

42:37.760 --> 42:41.760
Bly took out his sextant and looked at the sun.

42:41.760 --> 42:45.760
Then he made some calculations.

42:45.760 --> 42:47.760
We're a long way from land.

42:47.760 --> 42:49.760
He told the men in the boat.

42:49.760 --> 42:52.760
We don't have much food or water.

42:52.760 --> 42:54.760
But we can survive.

42:54.760 --> 42:58.760
I promise you, we can survive.

42:58.760 --> 43:00.760
Discipline, men.

43:00.760 --> 43:01.760
Discipline.

43:01.760 --> 43:06.760
Captain Bly took the boat to some small islands.

43:06.760 --> 43:09.760
They bought some food and water from the people there.

43:09.760 --> 43:14.760
After that they were ready to begin their journey.

43:17.760 --> 43:19.760
Chapter 10.

43:19.760 --> 43:22.760
Land.

43:22.760 --> 43:28.760
It was hot on the small boat and there was no protection from the sun.

43:28.760 --> 43:32.760
After a week the men were hungry and thirsty.

43:32.760 --> 43:36.760
Captain Bly used his sextant every day.

43:36.760 --> 43:40.760
He tried to make his men feel better.

43:40.760 --> 43:41.760
We're sailors.

43:41.760 --> 43:42.760
He told them.

43:42.760 --> 43:45.760
We can survive hunger and thirst.

43:45.760 --> 43:49.760
And we have the discipline for this voyage.

43:49.760 --> 43:53.760
Captain Bly told the sailors that he had a plan.

43:53.760 --> 43:55.760
We'll go to the island of Tafoa.

43:55.760 --> 43:56.760
He said.

43:56.760 --> 43:59.760
We can buy more food and water there.

43:59.760 --> 44:02.760
The men believed in their captain.

44:02.760 --> 44:07.760
He was always calm and he always knew where the boat was.

44:07.760 --> 44:10.760
He was not afraid of the sea.

44:10.760 --> 44:14.760
They soon arrived at the island of Tafoa.

44:14.760 --> 44:21.760
At first the islanders were friendly and they brought the sailors food and drink.

44:21.760 --> 44:24.760
But soon they began to change.

44:24.760 --> 44:28.760
They attacked the sailors and killed one of them.

44:28.760 --> 44:33.760
Captain Bly gave the order to sail away from the island.

44:33.760 --> 44:39.760
Now they only had enough food and water for five days.

44:39.760 --> 44:41.760
Listen to me, men.

44:41.760 --> 44:43.760
Captain Bly said.

44:43.760 --> 44:46.760
We must sail to Koopang.

44:46.760 --> 44:50.760
But the journey will take fifty days.

44:50.760 --> 44:55.760
We must eat and drink very little.

44:55.760 --> 44:58.760
It will be difficult and dangerous.

44:58.760 --> 45:01.760
But we can do it.

45:01.760 --> 45:03.760
What do you say?

45:03.760 --> 45:05.760
Will you follow my orders?

45:05.760 --> 45:10.760
The sailors agreed to follow their captain's orders.

45:10.760 --> 45:13.760
The sea was full of sharks.

45:13.760 --> 45:15.760
They followed the boat.

45:15.760 --> 45:18.760
Don't put your hands in the water.

45:18.760 --> 45:21.760
Captain Bly told the sailors.

45:21.760 --> 45:24.760
The sharks are hungry too.

45:24.760 --> 45:27.760
The sea was flat and calm.

45:27.760 --> 45:30.760
The boat sailed through the waves.

45:30.760 --> 45:36.760
Suddenly the sea became rough and the boat moved from side to side.

45:36.760 --> 45:38.760
Tom was afraid.

45:38.760 --> 45:40.760
It's a whale!

45:40.760 --> 45:42.760
One of the sailors cried.

45:42.760 --> 45:47.760
Then Tom saw an enormous whale come out of the sea.

45:47.760 --> 45:50.760
The whale was larger than their boat.

45:50.760 --> 45:52.760
Captain Bly laughed.

45:52.760 --> 45:55.760
Don't be frightened, Mr. Barnes.

45:55.760 --> 45:56.760
He said kindly.

45:56.760 --> 45:59.760
Whales don't attack boats.

45:59.760 --> 46:01.760
The weather quickly changed.

46:01.760 --> 46:06.760
The sky was full of clouds and there was a strong wind.

46:06.760 --> 46:09.760
A storm is coming, sir.

46:09.760 --> 46:12.760
One of the sailors said to Captain Bly.

46:12.760 --> 46:15.760
Captain Bly saw that he was right.

46:15.760 --> 46:17.760
Take the sail down, men.

46:17.760 --> 46:19.760
He commanded.

46:19.760 --> 46:21.760
Soon the storm arrived.

46:21.760 --> 46:25.760
The waves were very big and the boat was full of water.

46:25.760 --> 46:31.760
The storm lasted all that day and continued all that night.

46:31.760 --> 46:35.760
The sailors were wet and tired.

46:35.760 --> 46:40.760
It was now the thirtieth day of their voyage in the boat.

46:40.760 --> 46:43.760
The men were exhausted.

46:43.760 --> 46:49.760
They wanted to rest, but they continued to obey Captain Bly's orders.

46:49.760 --> 46:52.760
Suddenly, one of the sailors looked up.

46:52.760 --> 46:54.760
A sail!

46:54.760 --> 46:55.760
He shouted.

46:55.760 --> 46:57.760
There's a ship over there, sir!

46:57.760 --> 46:59.760
It was true.

46:59.760 --> 47:02.760
They saw a sail in the distance.

47:02.760 --> 47:04.760
They started to shout.

47:04.760 --> 47:06.760
They wanted the ship to see them.

47:06.760 --> 47:12.760
They shouted for a long time, but the ship did not see their boat.

47:12.760 --> 47:16.760
After a while, they could not see the sail anymore.

47:16.760 --> 47:19.760
The men were sad now.

47:19.760 --> 47:21.760
They had no hope.

47:21.760 --> 47:23.760
We're going to die!

47:23.760 --> 47:25.760
One of them said.

47:25.760 --> 47:28.760
My sextant, please, Mr. Barnes.

47:28.760 --> 47:31.760
Captain Bly said to Tom.

47:31.760 --> 47:34.760
I must discover where we are.

47:34.760 --> 47:40.760
Captain Bly looked through the sextant and wrote some numbers on a piece of paper.

47:40.760 --> 47:42.760
Good news, men.

47:42.760 --> 47:44.760
He told the sailors.

47:44.760 --> 47:46.760
It was near land.

47:46.760 --> 47:48.760
How many days, sir?

47:48.760 --> 47:51.760
One of the sailors wanted to know.

47:51.760 --> 47:52.760
Ten days?

47:52.760 --> 47:54.760
Two weeks?

47:54.760 --> 47:56.760
Captain Bly told him.

47:56.760 --> 48:01.760
And then food and water, as much as we want.

48:01.760 --> 48:05.760
The sailors looked at their captain with respect.

48:05.760 --> 48:08.760
They trusted him now.

48:08.760 --> 48:10.760
He was a good navigator.

48:10.760 --> 48:13.760
They started to hope again.

48:13.760 --> 48:18.760
It was the 47th day at sea in the boat.

48:18.760 --> 48:21.760
The men had no strength.

48:21.760 --> 48:25.760
It was difficult for them to raise and lower the sail.

48:25.760 --> 48:28.760
They needed food and water.

48:28.760 --> 48:33.760
It was a hot day, and some of the sailors were asleep.

48:33.760 --> 48:36.760
Captain Bly talked to Tom.

48:36.760 --> 48:39.760
They're good men, he said.

48:39.760 --> 48:42.760
They have discipline, Mr. Barnes.

48:42.760 --> 48:50.760
The Navy needs discipline, discipline, and good navigation.

48:50.760 --> 48:57.760
On the 12th of June, 1789, one of the sailors gave a shout.

48:57.760 --> 48:58.760
Lancer!

48:58.760 --> 49:01.760
I can see land over there!

49:01.760 --> 49:04.760
The other sailors woke up.

49:04.760 --> 49:06.760
They looked out of the boat.

49:06.760 --> 49:07.760
It's true!

49:07.760 --> 49:08.760
They cried.

49:08.760 --> 49:09.760
Lancer!

49:09.760 --> 49:11.760
Land!

49:11.760 --> 49:14.760
Captain Bly smiled at them.

49:14.760 --> 49:17.760
It is land, indeed.

49:17.760 --> 49:18.760
He told them.

49:18.760 --> 49:21.760
This is Timor.

49:21.760 --> 49:24.760
Soon they were on land.

49:24.760 --> 49:30.760
Their journey of 7,000 kilometers was over.

49:33.760 --> 49:35.760
Epilogue.

49:35.760 --> 49:38.760
Tom returned to England.

49:38.760 --> 49:43.760
He became a good officer and was popular with the sailors.

49:43.760 --> 49:52.760
Two years after the mutiny, another British ship, HMS Pandora, arrived in Tahiti.

49:52.760 --> 49:58.760
The sailors from HMS Pandora looked for the mutineers from the bounty.

49:58.760 --> 50:03.760
They found 14 sailors and took them back to England.

50:03.760 --> 50:11.760
But during the journey, the ship hit a rock near Australia and some of the mutineers died.

50:11.760 --> 50:14.760
Other ships took them back to England.

50:14.760 --> 50:18.760
When they arrived, there was a trial.

50:18.760 --> 50:22.760
Mutiny was a very serious crime.

50:22.760 --> 50:26.760
Three mutineers received the death penalty.

50:26.760 --> 50:31.760
But the judges decided that the others were innocent.

50:32.760 --> 50:34.760
The years passed.

50:34.760 --> 50:39.760
Tom became a successful captain and commanded his own ship.

50:39.760 --> 50:47.760
He wanted to know about Fletcher Christian and the bounty, but there was no information.

50:47.760 --> 51:00.760
Then, in 1808, 19 years after the mutiny, an American ship came to the small island of Pitcairn in the Pacific.

51:00.760 --> 51:05.760
Captain Folger discovered a white man on the island.

51:05.760 --> 51:12.760
He was a sailor called Adams, the only survivor of the bounty mutineers.

51:12.760 --> 51:17.760
Now he was old and he had a family.

51:17.760 --> 51:21.760
Adams told Captain Folger the story of the bounty.

51:21.760 --> 51:25.760
We took the bounty back to Tahiti after the mutiny.

51:25.760 --> 51:34.760
He explained, some Polynesian men and Tahiti women came with us and we sailed here to Pitcairn.

51:34.760 --> 51:37.760
We burned the bounty.

51:37.760 --> 51:43.760
We didn't want people to find it because we were afraid of punishment.

51:43.760 --> 51:45.760
What happened then?

51:45.760 --> 51:48.760
Captain Folger wanted to know.

51:48.760 --> 51:50.760
It was terrible.

51:50.760 --> 51:56.760
Adams said, we argued with the Polynesian men all the time.

51:56.760 --> 52:02.760
We fought a battle against them and Fletcher Christian died.

52:02.760 --> 52:09.760
Some of the mutineers died in the battle as well and we killed all the Polynesian men.

52:09.760 --> 52:11.760
But you're the only survivor.

52:11.760 --> 52:16.760
Captain Folger exclaimed, what happened after the battle?

52:16.760 --> 52:19.760
It was the Tahitian women.

52:19.760 --> 52:26.760
Adams explained, they weren't happy with us and they killed most of us.

52:26.760 --> 52:29.760
The rest died of illness.

52:29.760 --> 52:34.760
Captain Folger brought the news about the bounty to England.

52:34.760 --> 52:41.760
Now Tom finally knew the truth about his friend Fletcher Christian and the other mutineers.

52:41.760 --> 52:47.760
He was sad when he thought about his friend from the early days of his career.

52:47.760 --> 52:53.760
Then he remembered again the words of the old sailor at the port.

52:53.760 --> 52:57.760
That's one of the two things you must do.

52:57.760 --> 53:01.760
Learn everything you can.

53:01.760 --> 53:04.760
And what's the second thing I must do?

53:04.760 --> 53:05.760
That's easy.

53:05.760 --> 53:11.760
The old sailor replied, obey your captain.

53:11.760 --> 53:13.760
It was good advice.

53:13.760 --> 53:15.760
Thought Tom.

53:15.760 --> 53:24.760
Fletcher made a bad mistake when he mutineered against Captain Bligh.

53:24.760 --> 53:27.760
Listening activity.

53:27.760 --> 53:30.760
What is your name?

53:30.760 --> 53:32.760
My name's John Fletcher.

53:32.760 --> 53:35.760
How old are you?

53:35.760 --> 53:37.760
Eighteen.

53:37.760 --> 53:39.760
Where were you born?

53:39.760 --> 53:41.760
Newcastle.

53:41.760 --> 53:43.760
Where do you live now?

53:43.760 --> 53:45.760
London.

53:45.760 --> 53:47.760
Are you still a sailor?

53:47.760 --> 53:49.760
No.

53:49.760 --> 53:53.760
I can't work in the Navy because I'm here on trial.

53:53.760 --> 53:57.760
I now work as a carpenter.

53:57.760 --> 54:00.760
What was your role in the mutiny?

54:00.760 --> 54:08.760
I didn't want to take part in the mutiny, but there was no more room in the small boat to go with the captain.

54:08.760 --> 54:16.760
I returned to England when they came to find us on the island of Tahiti.

54:38.760 --> 54:41.760
You

